      language: "Greek",
      definition: "It is finished, it is accomplished, it is completed — perfect passive indicative of 'teleō' (to complete, to fulfil, to bring to its intended end). The perfect tense indicates completed action with ongoing results.",
      usage: "John 19:30 — 'he said, It is finished (tetelestai).' Archaeological papyri from the first century use the same word on paid receipts and tax documents to indicate a debt fully settled. When Jesus spoke tetelestai, His Roman and Greek-speaking audience would have understood the commercial and legal register immediately: the account is closed, the debt discharged, nothing outstanding. The Greek perfect tense adds the theological precision: this completion is permanent. The cross was not a tragedy that God subsequently redeemed — it was the completion of the plan God had been executing since Genesis 3:15.",
      connection: "Tetelestai is the answer to every attempt to add works, performance, or worthiness to the basis of salvation. 'It is finished' means the work of redemption is complete — not mostly complete, not requiring your supplement. Complete. Your role is not to add to it but to receive it, trust it, and live in the freedom it has purchased. Every time you feel you must earn God's approval, remember: tetelestai. Paid in full.",
