        "The women were the first witnesses to the empty tomb and the first to see the risen Jesus — a detail no first-century Jewish fraud would have invented. In first-century Jewish culture, women's testimony was inadmissible in court. If you were fabricating resurrection accounts for maximum credibility, you would have used male witnesses.",
        "1 Corinthians 15:6 records that the risen Jesus appeared to 'above five hundred brethren at once' — most of whom were still alive when Paul wrote (c. AD 54-55). This is an implicit invitation to verify: ask them. The resurrection was not proclaimed in a context where verification was impossible — it was proclaimed in Jerusalem within weeks, where the tomb was accessible and the witnesses were alive.",
        "The empty tomb is historically attested by both Christian and Jewish sources: the Jewish authorities did not dispute the empty tomb — they responded to it by claiming the disciples had stolen the body (Matthew 28:11-15). A stolen body is an explanation for an empty tomb, not a denial of it. The emptiness was not in question. The explanation was.",
        "The resurrection transformed a group of terrified, hiding disciples into men and women who preached across the Roman Empire, endured imprisonment and torture, and died for their testimony. The disciples' transformation — from the cowering men of Good Friday to the bold preachers of Acts 2 — requires an explanation. The resurrection is the most historically satisfying one."
